This article is about an executive order signed by President Barack Obama. The executive order amends Executive Order 12777, which deals with the implementation of the Federal Water Pollution Control Act and the Oil Pollution Act. The amendment specifically focuses on the adjustment of liability limits for vessels, onshore facilities, deepwater ports, and offshore facilities. The President delegates certain functions to various departments and agencies, such as the Secretary of the department in which the Coast Guard operates, the Administrator, the Secretary of Transportation, the Secretary of the Interior, the Secretary of Energy, and the Attorney General. The functions include adjusting liability limits to reflect increases in the Consumer Price Index and reporting to Congress on the desirability of adjusting these limits. The executive order also clarifies that it does not affect existing authorities or create any new rights or benefits enforceable against the United States or any other party.